<Group labelreference="L18" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" size="16" layout="Normal"><Font size="16">There are a few points to note about the irrotational vortex.  First, it is singular at the origin.  Second, the vorticity away from the origin is zero (hence the name).  The flip side of this is that ALL the vorticity is concentrated at the origin (as a delta function).  Third, the rate of strain tensor shows that all the entries decay with distance from the origin.</Font></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L6">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">F2 := proc(N,t,X,XP)                   # First order system
   XP[1] := -0.5*X[2];
   XP[2] := 0.5*X[1];
end proc;
DEplot(F2,[x(t),y(t)],t=0..20,number=2,[[x(0)=.5,y(0)=0],[x(0)=1,y(0)=0],
[x(0)=2,y(0)=0]],stepsize=.01,title=`Path lines Solid Body Vortex`,
color=[.3*y(t)*(x(t)-1),x(t)*(1-y(t)),.1],linecolor=[black,blue,red],arrows=MEDIUM,
method=rkf45,font=[COURIER,16],titlefont=[COURIER,16]);DEplot(F2,x(t),t=0..20,number=2,[[x(0)=0.5,y(0)=0],[x(0)=1,y(0)=0],
[x(0)=2,y(0)=0]],stepsize=.01,title=`x vs. t Solid Body Vortex`,
linecolor=[black,blue,red],arrows=none,
